not change over time. If you want to change the Constitution, youeither amend it or scrap it for a new one! &#10;Except that Article III states, &quot;In all the other Cases before mentioned, the supreme Court shall have appellate Jurisdiction, both as to Law and Fact, with such Exceptions, and under such Regulations as the Congress shall make.&quot; There is nothing in Article III that says Supreme Court decisions have the force of law. It is not the role of the federal courts to legislate! &#10;See above.&#10;Actually, there is nothing in what was quoted that even remotely says this.&#10;As is what you think. The Constitution means exactly and only what it says.&#10;If you want the Supreme Court to have the authority to interpret the Constitution and if you want the Supreme Court to have the authority to legislate from the bench, then feel free to get enough support to amend the Constitution. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1181" language="en" documentId="1980" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="Chancellor" date="7th September 2007 01:20 PM" docType="forumpost" origUrl="http://www.volconvo.com/forums/showthread.php?t=11753&amp;page=8" topic="prayer-in-schools" thumbsUp="0" thumbsDown="0" origId="1980" notes="" title="The Bible in Public Schools"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="126"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="127" end="411"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="412" end="786"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="51" sofa="1" begin="787" end="797"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="55" sofa="1" begin="798" end="873"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="59" sofa="1" begin="874" end="949"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="63" sofa="1" begin="950" end="1181"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47 51 55 59 63"/></xmi:XMI>